<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY PLAYS CATCH UP ON GOLF COURSES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE BERKMAN, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Orange County mattress magnate Wayne Simmons plans to drive from his Anaheim 
Hills residence to Dana Point every other week this summer to play golf at the 
Links at Monarch Beach, shunning a country club located much closer to his 
home. 
</P>
<P>
Simmons, owner of W. Simmons Mattress Co. in Cerritos, says it doesn't bother 
him a bit to fight freeway traffic for 45 minutes and pay the highest green 
fees in Orange County -- $50 on weekdays, $75 on weekends -- to play a 
first-class course with two holes right on the ocean. 
</P>
<P>
There are plenty of people who share Simmons' enthusiasm, and their apparent 
willingness to play golf at nearly any cost is prompting developers to 
transform hundreds of acres of valuable land in Orange County into upscale golf 
courses. 
</P>
<P>
At least 12 new golf courses are being planned or built in Orange County, most 
in conjunction with expensive south county housing developments. Their 
completion will increase the number of public and private courses in the county 
to 44. 
</P>
<P>
The new facilities are billed as premier courses, designed by golfing 
luminaries and architects such as Jack Nicklaus, Gary Player, Robert Trent 
Jones Jr., Tom Fazio, Tom Weiskopf, Jay Morrish and Ted Robinson. And all will 
cost much more to play than most golfers are accustomed to paying. 
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of golfers and a limited supply of courses has sparked a 
golf course construction spree across the country. Developer interest has been 
stoked by higher fees, which make operating courses more lucrative than in the 
past. 
</P>
<P>
Contributing to the boom in Southern California is the ability to use golf 
courses to satisfy open space mandates and the recognition that the presence of 
golf courses will increase adjoining property values. 
</P>
<P>
From 1970 through 1988, the number of golfers in the United States more than 
doubled to 23.4 million from 11.2 million, according to the National Golf 
Foundation. The national golfing population is expected to expand to 30 million 
by the year 2000. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Lagged Behind in Construction 
</P>
<P>
The foundation believes that demand is sufficient to support construction of 
400 or more golf courses annually between now and the year 2000. Only 211 new 
courses were opened in 1988. Golf, which seemed to take a back seat to tennis 
as the "in" sport of the early 1970s, is enjoying a resurgence in the 1980s. 
The national tennis population has fallen to 20 million from a peak of 40 
million in the late 1970s, according to the American Tennis Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
The change is generally attributed to the aging of America's baby boomers, many 
of whom are now looking for less strenuous forms of recreation that also offer 
social and professional payoffs. 
</P>
<P>
Orange County, with an estimated 214,000 golfers, long has lagged behind other 
areas in construction of new golf courses. National Golf Foundation statistics 
show that in 1987, the county had 4,653 golfers for each 18-hole course. That 
compared to 3,620 golfers per 18 holes statewide and 2,056 golfers per 18 holes 
nationally. California had the fewest courses per capita of any state in the 
nation. 
</P>
<P>
The demand in Orange County is dramatized by the long lines that form every day 
before dawn outside of pro shops at lower-cost public courses. Early rising is 
a required regimen for golfers who stand in line not to play that day, but to 
make reservations for a week later. 
</P>
<P>
The new courses are expected to attract golfers who want to escape the jammed 
municipal courses and are willing to pay more for some elbow room at the 
upscale facilities. The new courses also claim that they will be a cut above 
most municipal courses in quality. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
High Fees 
</P>
<P>
Gene Krekorian, senior vice president of Economic Research Associates in Los 
Angeles, said no one in Orange County is building the kind of golf course that 
is needed most: those with fees of $10 to $15. Even so, he said, there are 
plenty of golfers who will support the more expensive courses. 
</P>
<P>
By traditional standards, the new courses are certainly pricey. 
</P>
<P>
At the Tustin Ranch Golf Course, an undulating expanse of manicured turf, 
pools, waterfalls and 2,000 trees that is making its debut Monday, golfers will 
be asked to pay $45 on weekdays and $60 on weekends. 
</P>
<P>
Charges at Tijeras Creek Golf Course, scheduled to open next summer in the 
developing foothill community of Rancho Santa Margarita, are expected to run 
about $25 on weekdays and $50 on weekends. 
</P>
<P>
And two public golf courses that the Irvine Co. plans to develop along the 
coast just south of Corona Del Mar as part of a resort project are expected to 
top the $50 and $75 fees at the Links at Monarch Beach, currently the county's 
most expensive course. 
</P>
<P>
With fees like these, developers can not only recover all of their development 
costs but also pay for part of the land underlying the course, said Krekorian. 
</P>
<P>
Some developers, however, have no interest in operating golf courses and plan 
to recapture their costs by turning the courses into private clubs and selling 
memberships at prices that would have seemed astonishing only a few years ago. 
</P>
<P>
Initiation fees for memberships in the new private courses range from $8,500 at 
Pacific Golf Club in San Clemente to $75,000 at Marbella Golf &amp; Country 
Club in San Juan Capistrano. In addition, members must pay monthly dues in the 
hundreds of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
Despite the high cost, memberships are selling briskly. Although the golf 
course and clubhouse at Marbella have yet to open, all but 52 of 300 club 
memberships have been sold, said Ken Olson, corporate broker for the 
developers. And at Pacific Golf Club, memberships are being snapped up at a 
rate of 50 a month, according to Bob Hayward, general manager of the 27-hole 
course. 
</P>
<P>
In some cases, cities are encouraging the development of public golf courses. 
Jay Pierce, director of land development for an Irvine Co. subsidiary that is 
developing Tustin Ranch, said the Tustin City Council insisted on construction 
of a showcase public golf course as part of the 9,000-home community. 
</P>
<P>
"We wouldn't have been able to build houses out there if it weren't for the 
golf course," Pierce said. 
</P>
<P>
Christine Singleton, Tustin's community development director, conceded that 
fees at the new course will be too rich for the blood of some Tustin residents. 
Even so, she said, the city is getting a free golf course that is "far better 
than what the city could afford to construct." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
More Open Space 
</P>
<P>
Although Orange County planning officials will not let developers substitute 
golf courses for required parkland in planned community developments, they will 
count courses toward general open space requirements. To that extent, the 
courses wind up generating revenue from land that would not be developed 
otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
Eric Jessen, chief of planning and acquisition for Orange County Harbors, 
Beaches and Parks, said the county planning commission has shown "a strong 
interest in golf courses." 
</P>
<P>
Jessen said that in return for giving developers open space credit for golf 
courses, the county in recent years has begun filing deed restrictions to be 
sure that the courses will be retained forever as open space and not later 
converted to housing. 
</P>
<P>
In areas where land proposed for a golf course is flat and easily buildable, 
Jessen said, the county generally gets more open space than it otherwise could 
have demanded from a developer. 
</P>
<P>
But as a rule, golf courses are not built because of the green fees they will 
generate or the open space requirements they will satisfy. Krekorian said the 
most compelling economic incentive is the opportunity to increase the prices of 
lots and homes in surrounding communities, especially those directly 
overlooking the fairway. 
</P>
<P>
"The reason they do it is for the real estate premiums that in many cases more 
than make up the cost of the land being used for the golf course," Krekorian 
said. "You can't afford to buy a piece of property and build a golf course and 
(expect to) make money. You need to do it as part of an overall community 
development." 
</P>
<P>
Garth Chambers, developer of the Dove Canyon community in southeastern Orange 
County, figures that his costs for golf course development include $6 million 
for the land, $6 million for construction of the course, $12 million for the 
clubhouse and $3 million to subsidize the private club until it is 
self-supporting. He said that if the state Department of Corporations approves 
his plan to sell 479 golf club memberships for $60,000 each, he will reap a 
very modest profit on his $27 million investment. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Water Features 
</P>
<P>
But Chambers said he expects that the private country club atmosphere created 
by the golf course will add 30% to average property values within the 
1,300-home community. 
</P>
<P>
According to real estate sales people, home buyers cherish a view of a golf 
course second only to an ocean view. A home by a fairway often will sell for 
$50,000 to $300,000 more than the same model home just out of sight of the golf 
course, they said. 
</P>
<P>
"If a unit is directly on the golf course, the typical premium is about 20% of 
the base price. So if it were a $400,000 single-family home, it would get a 
$80,000 premium for the course," said Ken Agid, a national real estate 
marketing analyst. 
</P>
<P>
The size of the golf course premium, marketing experts said, also depends on 
whether the golf course is private and has water features. 
</P>
<P>
"If you add water, they will pay an additional premium," said Ted Robinson, a 
Laguna Beach golf course architect who designed the new courses in Santa 
Margarita and Tustin. 
</P>
<P>
"For every dollar spent on waterscapes, we will get $3 to $4 in increased real 
estate values," said Robinson, who specializes in "babbling brooks and 
waterfalls." 
</P>
<P>
At Marbella, sales of lots over the past year have been at least as hot as 
sales of golf club memberships. "We had 215 lots for sale, and they are all 
gone but for five. People love to live on golf courses," said J. Richard (Rick) 
McMichael, president of Fairway Land Co., a Laguna Niguel firm that is creating 
the exclusive golf community with two Bay Area developers. 
</P>
<P>
McMichael noted that home buyers don't seem discouraged by the company's 
warnings that living near a golf course can pose dangers from errant golf 
balls. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Essential to Resorts 
</P>
<P>
Even before Coto de Caza has enough golf club members to support one golf 
course, the developer of the fashionable community is planning a second course 
to open in mid-1991. The reason, said John Yelverton, president of the 
California division of Arvida, which is developing the project with Chevron 
Land Development Co., is to provide more golf course settings for more lots. He 
said a golf course view adds $60,000 to $90,000 to the price tag of each 
buildable lot. 
</P>
<P>
Nor does living on golf courses appeal only to golfers. "Typically, 75% of the 
buyers in a golf course-oriented community do not belong to the club or play 
golf," said Agid. "Twenty-five percent of the buyers are attracted by the open 
space and manicured setting, and another 50% by the associated benefits, such 
as the prestige and future real estate values." 
</P>
<P>
Golf courses are deemed essential to south Orange County's bid to become a 
major destination resort area. 
</P>
<P>
The Monarch Beach course is important to the nearby Ritz-Carlton Hotel and will 
be a big draw for two other hotels that are planned on its perimeter. In tandem 
with the new hotel projects, Townsend said, the golf course will be expanded 
and redesigned. 
</P>
<P>
Henry Scheilein, general manager of the Ritz Carlton, said he dearly values an 
agreement that reserves for the hotel half of the Monarch Beach tee-off times. 
"A resort couldn't label itself a resort without a golf course," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Scheilein said, many of his hotel guests are Japanese businessmen who 
are "wild about golf." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Jay Pierce, Irvine Co. director of land development, and Richard Hess, 
director of construction, at Tustin Ranch Golf Course. KEN HIVELY / Los Angeles 
Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
GOLF; GOLF COURSES; ORANGE COUNTY -- DEVELOPMENT AND REDEVELOPMENT; REAL ESTATE 
INVESTMENT 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA070989-0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 79732 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 9, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part 4; Page 2; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1567 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WALL STREET / JOHN CRUDELE: PSSST! DO I HAVE SOME 'JOURNALOSSIP' FOR YOU 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN CRUDELE, JOHN CRUDELE is a financial columnist for the New York Post. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I'm going to spread some rumors that were told to me last week by a couple of 
stock traders. 
</P>
<P>
Specifically, I'm going to tell you that I hear (as in "I hear a rumor") that a 
group of investors purchased a 3% stake in Paramount Communications. 
</P>
<P>
In case that one doesn't interest you, I'm also going to tell you that I hear 
(again, as in "rumor") that someone might be interested in acquiring Perry 
Drug. 
</P>
<P>
I'm not going to check out either rumor, quite frankly, because it's too much 
trouble. And besides, I think that I can trust the guys who told me the rumors 
even if they do have a vested interested in spreading them. 
</P>
<P>
I could call the companies involved, but they'll just say "no comment." And 
phoning investment bankers during the summer is futile -- most are on vacation 
for three months. 
</P>
<P>
So I'll just be honest with you, the reader, and say that the Paramount and 
Perry stories are just "rumors." Phew, now my conscience is clear. 
</P>
<P>
With the above exercise, I have become a practitioner of a new and dangerous 
form of para-journalism that I'll call journalossip. I've done nothing wrong, 
legally. I've just given the professional trader what he wants -- rumors. 
</P>
<P>
And so what if the amateur stock buyer loses a lot of money if these rumors 
don't come true. On Wall Street, I'll be a hero. 
</P>
<P>
Journalossip is to business journalism what those tabloid TV news shows are to 
the real broadcast news industry. But journalossip is worse -- because small 
investors can get hold of these rumors, not recognize them for what they are 
and endanger their financial health. 
</P>
<P>
While financial journalossip has been around and growing for years, it reached 
a milestone recently with the introduction of something called the "Traders 
&amp; Investors Alert," a phone-in service with a "900" telephone number that 
will give any rumor lover an earful of corporate takeover gossip for just $1.95 
a minute. 
</P>
<P>
How popular is the service? Barry Davis, the service's "broadcaster," says 
Traders &amp; Investors Alert has more than 1,500 regular customers after being 
in business just over seven months. And it probably will generate $4 million in 
revenue this year. 
</P>
<P>
Davis admits that most of the information on his "whisper" report -- as he 
calls it -- is nothing more than unconfirmed rumors. "The difference," he says, 
"is we lend some sophistication to the rumors because we check the (New York 
Stock Exchange trading) floor on the quality of the buying." 
</P>
<P>
In other words, Davis tries to see if the big professional traders are putting 
their money where their mouth is by buying stock based on the rumors they are 
spreading. 
</P>
<P>
Davis is not a journalist by training. He says he was a stockbroker and 
insurance salesman until he lost his licenses. He now lists his profession as 
"broadcaster," but he also passes his time by trading some of the stocks that 
he's talking about on the whisper wire for his own account. 
</P>
<P>
The popularity of Traders &amp; Investors Alert raises a host of side 
questions: Is there a conflict of interest if Davis trades stocks that he's 
spreading rumors about on his wire? And should he be allowed to call himself a 
journalist and claim protection under the First Amendment? 
</P>
<P>
But for now, let's just discuss one thing: the phenomena of rumor mongering and 
why Wall Street just can't seem to get its fill of gossip. 
</P>
<P>
One trader last week offered this opinion: "The only action we have right now 
are quasi-deals, possible deals and rumors. There aren't enough real takeovers 
to go around at this point," he added. 
</P>
<P>
So, he says, in order to earn a living, traders must buy stocks on rumors, ride 
them as high as they can and sell the stocks before everyone moves on to the 
next rumor. 
</P>
<P>
Here's where Davis and the rumor mongering press come in. The more efficient 
that the press is in helping spread a rumor, the longer that traders get to 
ride the stock higher. 
</P>
<P>
Davis makes a good point. He says he is doing nothing different from other 
journalists these days. But he doesn't pretend -- like some journalists do -- 
to check the accuracy of rumors. 
</P>
<P>
As for capitalizing on people's desire to hear takeover rumors, Davis says: 
"This is the way the world is. Rumors make stocks go up and down. I'm teaching 
people how to play the takeover game." 
</P>
<P>
"It's a sick society that wants to get rich overnight," says Davis, adding that 
other phone-line services that he offers -- like one that gives a technical 
interpretation of the stock market -- get far fewer calls than the rumor hot 
line. 
</P>
<P>
Rumor mongering is likely to get worse. Since it's summer, there aren't likely 
to be many real takeover deals announced in the next few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
And since the stock market has been weak recently because of recession fears, 
traders and brokers will probably have to continue to make money off "special 
situations," Wall Street's polite term for stocks rumored to be takeover 
targets. 
</P>
<P>
Which gets me back to the role of journalossip. 
</P>
<P>
Am I, as a journalist, actually doing my readers a service by spreading 
unconfirmed rumors about Perry Drug and Paramount? 
</P>
<P>
Readers may think so as long as the price of Paramount and Perry rise after I 
spread the rumor. But when stock prices turn lower -- as they will someday -- 
those same readers will regret the day that they began playing takeover rumors. 
</P>
<P>
Just ask anyone who was speculating in takeover stocks in October, 1987. A lot 
of people probably swore off speculating in the stock market after that. 
</P>
<P>
Here's more on hidden corporate assets that could lead to takeovers: 
</P>
<P>
Probably the least hidden of all assets in America is land. It's just too hard 
to conceal. 
</P>
<P>
But while some companies, like retailers, obviously own valuable real estate, 
there are many other companies whose land holdings aren't so apparent. Wall 
Street has spent years exploring corporate landholdings, but the recent 
takeover of NWA Corp. -- which came about after it was discovered that the 
airline's secretly owned property in Tokyo was worth hundreds of millions of 
dollars -- has rekindled interest in the subject. 
</P>
<P>
Now companies as diverse as computer manufacturers, farming concerns and mobile 
home manufacturers are coming under the microscope -- or, more accurately, the 
surveyor's scope. 
</P>
<P>
Michael Metz, a managing director at Oppenheimer &amp; Co., says Data General 
Corp., for instance, has facilities on real estate near Boston and in Southern 
California that is so valuable that if the land and buildings were sold and the 
proceeds given to stockholders, he estimates that it could mean a $10- to 
$15-a-share payout. 
</P>
<P>
And Data General's stock is only selling at about $17 a share. 
</P>
<P>
As I mentioned several weeks ago, some of the older airlines are believed to 
have foreign and domestic real estate that was bought quite accidentally 
decades ago but is now worth small fortunes. 
</P>
<P>
The same accidental purchases of real estate have blessed companies in other 
industries. 
</P>
<P>
Metz says that Coachman Industries, whose stock sells for around $9 a share, 
Skyliner Corp. (around $17) and Fleetwood Enterprises (around $26) all have 
stumbled into the ownership of some valuable real estate. 
</P>
<P>
The three mobile home manufacturers located their factories on prime property 
just off major highways to facilitate shipping. And now that same real estate 
has risen sharply in value. 
</P>
<P>
Hotel chains, obviously, own valuable parcels of land. A piece of property that 
Hilton Corp. owns in Hawaii, for instance, could be the crown jewel that leads 
to the acquisition of the company. Even McDonald's Corp., the hamburger chain, 
has erected its golden arches on some pieces of property that have turned 
platinum over the years. 
</P>
<P>
"There are a lot of industries whose primary business isn't real estate but 
which have valuable real estate assets," says Roderick MacIver, a specialist in 
hidden real estate assets who heads his own firm in Basking Ridge, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
Railroads, water utilities, agricultural companies, forest products companies 
and industrial companies have all stumbled into valuable land holdings, says 
MacIver. 
</P>
<P>
His most successful pick was Alexander &amp; Baldwin Inc., an agricultural and 
shipping company that owns 95,000 choice acres in Hawaii and California. 
</P>
<P>
If you invest in the stock market, should you be cheering a slowdown in 
economic growth or an acceleration in growth? 
</P>
<P>
Oddly enough, the answer these days seems to be neither. The stock market has 
put itself in the puzzling position of being afraid of accelerating growth 
because it could bring with it inflation and higher interest rates, and even 
more wary of an economic slowdown because it will hurt corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
Stock prices lately have been looking on the negative side of all economic 
statistics. "A month ago there was nothing but ecstasy. Now you see nothing but 
problems," says William King, a trader for Prescott, Ball &amp; Turben in 
Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
Next Friday, there will be a lot more for the stock market to worry about. The 
government is scheduled to report how much producer prices rose in June. The 
estimates are that prices rose a modest 0.3%, compared to a 0.5% rise in May. 
Retail sales figures, industrial production levels and the capacity utilization 
rate for factories are also to be reported that day. 
</P>
<P>
"This is an extraordinarily difficult market to please," says Hugh Johnson, 
chief investment officer of First Albany Corp. "What the market really wants 
are numbers that say the economy is on a no-boom, no-bust trajectory." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
