<SECTION>
<P>
Part 1; Page 2; Column 1; Foreign Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
109 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An international association of computer professionals is planning to lift an 
eight-year ban on contacts with the Soviet Union because of improvements in 
human rights and scientific freedom. Bryan Kocher, president of the 
73,000-member Assn. for Computing Machinery, said the ban was adopted in 1981, 
primarily in response to the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, but that the 
reasons for it have "now disappeared." At the same time, the New York-based 
group has sent letters to Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping warning that 
professional exchanges with China could be jeopardized by Beijing's violent 
suppression of the country's pro-democracy movement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
ASSOCIATION FOR COMPUTING MACHINERY; HUMAN RIGHTS -- USSR; CHINA -- GOVERNMENT; 
COMPUTERS; COMPUTER INDUSTRY; CULTURAL RELATIONS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA070989-0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 80044 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 9, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
