<TEXT>
<P>
The Soviet Lithuanian Parliament passed a law that goes a step beyond national 
legislation in giving land back to farmers after decades of collectivization, 
the Lithuanian Communist Party daily Sovietskaya Litva reported. The law, which 
goes into effect Aug. 1, would -- without charge -- give farmers the land they 
now farm with the right to pass it on to heirs, the paper said. The law does 
not allow farmers to sell land, a step Moscow might view as a violation of the 
Communist ban on ownership of major private property. 
</P>
